    setty - prevents tty mode changes

  SSYYNNOOPPSSIISS

    setty [[-d||-q||-x]] [[-a]] [[[[+||-]]mode

  DDEESSCCRRIIPPTTIIOONN

    This command is a C-shell built-in command.

    The sseettttyy(1) command controls which tty modes the shell does not allow to
    change (see the section on terminal management in _tt_cc_ss_hh(1)). Using --dd, --
    qq or --xx tells sseettttyy to act on the 'edit', 'quote' or 'execute' set of tty
    modes respectively; without --dd, --qq or --xx, 'execute' is used.

    Without other arguments, sseettttyy lists the modes in the chosen set that are
    fixed on ('+mode') or off ('-mode'). The available modes, and thus the
    display, vary from system to system. With --aa, sseettttyy lists all tty modes in
    the chosen set, whether or not they are fixed. With ++mode, --mode, or mode,
    sseettttyy fixes mode on or off, or removes control from mode in the chosen
    set. For example, 'setty +echok echoe' fixes 'echok' mode on and allows
    commands to turn 'echoe' mode on or off, both when the shell is executing
    commands.

